PART 5: The norm form N(I(omega)) = a1^2 - a1*a2 + a2^2 - a1 + 1
======================================================================

  I(omega) = (1-a2) + (a1-a2)*omega where omega = e^{2pi*i/3}

  The norm in Z[omega]: N(a + b*omega) = a^2 - a*b + b^2

  With a = 1-a2, b = a1-a2:
  N = (1-a2)^2 - (1-a2)(a1-a2) + (a1-a2)^2
    = 1 - 2*a2 + a2^2 - (a1 - a2 - a1*a2 + a2^2) + a1^2 - 2*a1*a2 + a2^2
    = 1 - 2*a2 + a2^2 - a1 + a2 + a1*a2 - a2^2 + a1^2 - 2*a1*a2 + a2^2
    = a1^2 - a1*a2 + a2^2 - a1 - a2 + 1

  N(I(omega)) mod 3 distribution:
    N mod 3 = 0: 63 (31.5%)
    N mod 3 = 1: 137 (68.5%)

  N mod 3 = 2: NEVER
  This is the Eisenstein norm constraint: N(z) in Z[omega] is never 2 mod 3

  Distinct norms observed: 102
  Range: [1, 3184]
  Norms mod 3: always in {0, 1}: True

  N = a1^2 - a1*a2 + a2^2 - a1 - a2 + 1
  = (a1 - (a2+1)/2)^2 + 3/4*(a2-1)^2 + something...
  Completing the square in a1:
  N = (a1 - (a2+1)/2)^2 + (3/4)*a2^2 - (3/2)*a2 + 3/4
  = (a1 - (a2+1)/2)^2 + (3/4)*(a2 - 1)^2
  Wait, let me verify: (3/4)(a2-1)^2 = 3/4*a2^2 - 3/2*a2 + 3/4
  And (a1 - (a2+1)/2)^2 = a1^2 - a1*(a2+1) + (a2+1)^2/4
  = a1^2 - a1*a2 - a1 + a2^2/4 + a2/2 + 1/4
  Sum = a1^2 - a1*a2 - a1 + a2^2/4 + a2/2 + 1/4 + 3a2^2/4 - 3a2/2 + 3/4
  = a1^2 - a1*a2 - a1 + a2^2 - a2 + 1. YES!

  So N = (a1 - (a2+1)/2)^2 + (3/4)*(a2-1)^2 >= 0
  Equality iff a2=1 and a1=(a2+1)/2=1, i.e., a1=1, a2=1.
  N(1,1) = 0
  (a1,a2) = (1,1) found: False

